\begin_layout Section*

\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction to Rings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
ring
\series default
 is a triple 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,+,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 consisting of a set 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 together with two operations 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 (addition) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdot$
\end_inset

 (multiplication) such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,+)$
\end_inset

 forms an abelian group.
 This means
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Addition is associative: 
\begin_inset Formula $(a+b)+c=a+(b+c)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c\in R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Addition is commutative: 
\begin_inset Formula $a+b=b+a$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The identity element exists and is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

; there is an element 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a+0=a=0+a$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Inverses exist: For each 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, there exists an element 
\begin_inset Formula $-a$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a+(-a)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 forms a monoid.
 This means
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Multiplication is associative: 
\begin_inset Formula $(a\cdot b)\cdot c=a\cdot(b\cdot c)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c\in R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The identity element exists and is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

; there is an element 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $1\cdot a=a=a\cdot1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Multiplication is distributive with respect to addition.
 This means
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $a\cdot(b+c)=a\cdot b+a\cdot c$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c\in R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(b+c)\cdot a=b\cdot a+c\cdot a$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c\in R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
commutative ring 
\series default
if multiplication 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is commutative: for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=ba$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To clean notation, we abbreviate 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,+,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\cdot b$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $ab$
\end_inset

.
 We also denote the identity with respect to addition as 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and we denote the identity with respect to multiplication as 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
field 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is a ring which satisfies the property that every nonzero element has an
 inverse: if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in F\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

, then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in F\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $xy=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The set of integers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 equipped with the usual addition and multiplication operations is a ring.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 are rings where 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdot$
\end_inset

 denote the usual addition and multiplication operations.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ring Homomorphisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be rings.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:R\to S$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
ring homomorphism 
\series default
if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 preserves addition: 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a+b)=\varphi(a)+\varphi(b)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 preserves multiplication: 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(ab)=\varphi(a)\varphi(b)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 preserves the identity element: 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(1)=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\series bold
monomial 
\series default
in 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 variables (or indeterminates) 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 is a power product 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{\alpha}=x_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}\cdots x_{n}^{\alpha_{n}},\qquad\alpha=(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{n})\in\mathbb{N}^{n}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 are rings where 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdot$
\end_inset

 denote the usual addition and multiplication operations.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 be an integer.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{Z}/m\mathbb{Z},+,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is a ring.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A ring 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,+,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
commutative 
\series default
if multiplication is commutative.
 A ring 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,+,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 has 
\series bold
identity 
\series default
if there is 
\begin_inset Formula $1\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\cdot1=1\cdot a=a$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Unless otherwise stated, we will asume 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 always has an identity.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 is a noncommutative ring.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 Then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 we have 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $a\cdot0=0=0\cdot a$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(-a)b=-(ab)=a(-b)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(-a)(-b)=ab$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(-1)a=-a=1(-a)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 An nonzero element 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is said to be a 
\series bold
zero divisor 
\series default
if there exists a nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that either 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $ba=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

, then the zero divisors in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/n\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\bar{a}\in\mathbb{Z}/n\mathbb{Z}\mid a\neq0\mbox{ and gcd}(a,n)>1\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}\in\mathbb{Z}/n\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is a zero divisor.
 So there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{b}\in\mathbb{Z}/n\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{b}\neq\bar{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}\bar{b}=\bar{n}$
\end_inset

.
 This means 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=nm$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gcd}(a,n)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell,k\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $1=a\ell+nk$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,n\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a<n$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $d=\mbox{gcd}(a,n)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as a liear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 be the smallest positive integer that can be expressed as a linear combination
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $t=a\ell+nk$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell,k\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 We will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $t=d$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid a\ell+nk$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid t$
\end_inset

 .
 We show that 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mid a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mid n$
\end_inset

.
 To obtain a contradiciton, assume 
\begin_inset Formula $t\not\mid a$
\end_inset

.
 Then by Euclid's Algorithm, 
\begin_inset Formula $a=tg+r$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq r<t$
\end_inset

.
 So
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
r & =a-tg\\
 & =a-(a\ell+nk)g\\
 & =a(1-\ell g)+n(-kg)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is a linear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 which is strictly smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mid a$
\end_inset

.
 A similar argument show 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mid n$
\end_inset

 too.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mid a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mid n$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mid d$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mid d$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $t=d$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c\in R$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is not a zero divisor and if 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=ac$
\end_inset

, then either 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b=c$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=ac$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $a(b-c)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq0$
\end_inset

, then since 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is not a zero divisor, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $b-c=0$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $b=c$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 An element 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
unit 
\series default
if there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=1$
\end_inset

.
 We denote 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{\times}$
\end_inset

 to be the set of units of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}^{\times}=\{\pm1\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}^{\times}=\mathbb{Q}\setminus\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
division ring 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{\times}=R\setminus\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is also commutative, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
field
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Integral Domains
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An 
\series bold
integral domain 
\series default
is a commutative ring with non zero divisors.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every field is an integral domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/n\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is prime and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x},\overline{y}\in R\slash I$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}\overline{y}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $xy\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is prime, we either have 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in I$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, either 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{y}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $xy\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}\overline{y}=0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain, we either have 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{y}=0$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, either 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A finite integral domain is a field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R\setminus\{0\}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon R\to R$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(x)=ax
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is finite, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is bijective.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(b)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is a multiplicative inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Subring
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
subring 
\series default
of a ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $R'\subseteq R$
\end_inset

 that is a ring under the same 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdot$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and shares the same multiplicative identity.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is not a perfect square.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{d})=\{a+b\sqrt{d}\mid a,b\in\mathbb{Q}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with addition and multiplication rules give by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(a+b\sqrt{d})+(a'+b'\sqrt{d}) & =(a+a')+(b+b')\sqrt{d}\\
(a+b\sqrt{d})(a'+b'\sqrt{d}) & =(aa'+dbb')+(ab'+ba')\sqrt{d}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{d})$
\end_inset

 is a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{d})$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
More Examples of Rings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be two rings.
 Then we define the product of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R\times S=\{(r,s)\mid r\in R,\,s\in S\},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where addition and multiplication are defined pointwise.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Ring Homomorphisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be rings.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:R\to S$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
ring homomorphism 
\series default
if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a+b)=\varphi(a)+\varphi(b)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(ab)=\varphi(a)\varphi(b)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a ring homomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\times\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is completely determined by where it maps 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,1)$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi(a,b) & =\varphi((a,0)+(0,b))\\
 & =\varphi(a,0)+\varphi(0,b)\\
 & =a\varphi(1,0)+b\varphi(0,1).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)\in\mathbb{Z}\times\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,0)=(1,0)^{2}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(1,0)=\varphi(1,0)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(1,0)\in\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(0,1)\in\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus there are only four possible ring homomorphisms from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\times\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{0}(a,b)=0
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{1}(a,b)=a
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{2}(a,b)=b
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{3}(a,b)=a+b
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\times\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 It's easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{0},\varphi_{1},$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

 are ring homomorphisms, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{3}$
\end_inset

 is not: On the one hand,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{3}((a,b)(a',b'))=(a+b)(a'+b')=aa'+ab'+ba'+bb'
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
on the other hand 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{3}(aa',bb')=aa'+bb',
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{3}((a,b)(a',b'))-\varphi_{3}(aa',bb')=ab'+ba'$
\end_inset

 which is not necessarily equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathbb{Z}\to\mathbb{Z}/15\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is a ring homomorphism.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is completely determined by where it maps 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(m)=m\varphi(1)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(1)=\varphi(1)^{2}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $1=1^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(1)(\varphi(1)-\bar{1})=0.$
\end_inset

 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(1)\in\{\bar{0},\bar{1},\bar{6},\bar{10}\}$
\end_inset

.
 So there are four possible ring homomorphisms from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/15\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{0}(a)=\bar{0}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{1}(a)=\bar{a}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{2}(a)=\overline{6a}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{3}(a)=\overline{10a}
\]

\end_inset

All four maps are indeed ring homomorphisms.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{3}(ab)=\overline{10ab}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{3}(a)\varphi_{3}(b)=\overline{10a}\cdot\overline{10}b=\overline{10ab}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be rings and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:R\to S$
\end_inset

 be a ring homomorphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
kernel 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi=\{x\in R\mid\varphi(x)=0\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
image 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Im}\varphi=\{\varphi(x)\mid x\in R\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ideals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 A subset 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq R$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
left ideal 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 under addition and if 
\begin_inset Formula $rx\in I$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in R$
\end_inset

.
 A subset 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq R$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
right ideal 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 under addition and if 
\begin_inset Formula $xr\in I$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in R$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is both a left and right ideal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is commutative, then left and right ideals are the same.
 In general though, a left ideal may 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
be a right ideal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left\{ \left(\begin{smallmatrix}a & 0\\
b & 0
\end{smallmatrix}\right)\mid a,b\in\mathbb{Z}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a left ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}(\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is not a right ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}(\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{smallmatrix}a & 0\\
b & 0
\end{smallmatrix}\right)\left(\begin{smallmatrix}0 & 1\\
0 & 0
\end{smallmatrix}\right)=\left(\begin{smallmatrix}0 & a\\
0 & 0
\end{smallmatrix}\right)\notin I$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left\{ \left(\begin{smallmatrix}a & b\\
0 & 0
\end{smallmatrix}\right)\mid a,b\in\mathbb{Z}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a right ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}(\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is not a left ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}(\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left\{ \left(\begin{smallmatrix}a & b\\
c & d
\end{smallmatrix}\right)\mid a,b,c,d\in2\mathbb{Z}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a two-sided ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}(\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle m\rangle=m\mathbb{Z}=\{mk\mid k\in\mathbb{Z}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Any ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be rings and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:R\to S$
\end_inset

 be a ring homomorphism.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We know 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an abelian subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, since if 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\mbox{Ker}\varphi$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x-y)=\varphi(x)-\varphi(y)=0$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $x-y\in\mbox{Ker}\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mbox{Ker}\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(rx)=\varphi(r)\varphi(x)=0=\varphi(x)\varphi(r)=\varphi(xr)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $rx$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $xr$
\end_inset

 belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:\mathbb{Z}\to\mathbb{Z}_{m}$
\end_inset

 be the standard quotient map, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(a)=\bar{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\pi=m\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Quotient Rings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 under addition.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is abelian, we can form the group 
\begin_inset Formula $R/I$
\end_inset

.
 We define multiplication on 
\begin_inset Formula $R/I$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}\cdot\bar{b}:=\overline{ab}$
\end_inset

.
 Multilpication is well-defined if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is an two-sided ideal.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{a+x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{b+y}$
\end_inset

 are different representatives.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{a+x}\cdot\overline{b+y} & =\overline{(a+x)(b+y)}\\
 & =\overline{ab+ay+xb+xy}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In order for 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{ab+ay+xb+xy}=\overline{ab}$
\end_inset

, we need 
\begin_inset Formula $ay+xb+xy\in I$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 tells us 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 must be a left ideal.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $y=0$
\end_inset

 tells us 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 must be a right ideal.
 It's easy to see that multipication in 
\begin_inset Formula $R/I$
\end_inset

 is associative and distributive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be a two-sided ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R/I$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
quotient ring
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is commutative, then 
\begin_inset Formula $R/I$
\end_inset

 is commutative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 has identity, then 
\begin_inset Formula $R/I$
\end_inset

 has identity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
First Isomorphism Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (First Isomorphism Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:R\to S$
\end_inset

 is a ring homomorphism.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R/\mbox{Ker}\varphi\cong\mbox{Im}\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi:R/\mbox{Ker}\varphi\to\mbox{Im}\varphi$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(\overline{a})=\varphi(a)$
\end_inset

.
 This is well-defined since if 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{a+x}$
\end_inset

 is another representative, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi(\overline{a+x}) & =\varphi(a+x)\\
 & =\varphi(a)+\varphi(x)\\
 & =\varphi(a).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is a ring homomorphism since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi(\overline{a+b}) & =\varphi(a+b)\\
 & =\varphi(a)+\varphi(b)\\
 & =\psi(\bar{a})+\psi(\bar{b})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi(\overline{ab}) & =\varphi(ab)\\
 & =\varphi(a)\varphi(b)\\
 & =\psi(\bar{a})\psi(\bar{b}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is clearly injective and surjective, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 A subset 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset R$
\end_inset

 is a two-sided ideal if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\mbox{Ker}\varphi$
\end_inset

 for some ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:R\to S$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:R\to S$
\end_inset

 is a ring homomorphism, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:R\to R/I$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is the quotient map is a ring homomorphism with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\pi=I$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Second Isomorphism Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A+B=\{a+b\mid a\in A,\,b\in B\}$
\end_inset

 is a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B$
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A/A\cap B\cong(A+B)/B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are normal subroups of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 under additon, 
\begin_inset Formula $A+B$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 under addition too.
 Multiplication is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(a+b)(a'+b')=aa'+ab'+ba'+bb'\in A+B
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,a'\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b,b'\in B$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $A+B$
\end_inset

 is closed under multiplication.
 Left and right distributive laws hold because 
\begin_inset Formula $A+B$
\end_inset

 is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with the same addition and multiplication operations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A\cap B$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is an ideal, 
\begin_inset Formula $ax\in B$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $ax\in A$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $ax\in A\cap B$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Define a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A+B\to A/A\cap B$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a+b)=\overline{a}$
\end_inset

.
 This is well-defined since if 
\begin_inset Formula $a'+b'=a+b$
\end_inset

 is another representation, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi(a'+b') & =\overline{a'}\\
 & =\overline{a+b-b'}\\
 & =\overline{a},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $b-b'\in A\cap B$
\end_inset

.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is clearly surjective, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi=B$
\end_inset

.
 So by the first isomorphism theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $A/A\cap B\cong(A+B)/B$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Take 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A=12\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=15\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A+B=3\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B=60\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 So the second isomorphism theorem tells us 
\begin_inset Formula $12\mathbb{Z}/60\mathbb{Z}\cong3\mathbb{Z}/15\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Third Isomorphism Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I,J$
\end_inset

 be ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq J$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $J/I$
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R/I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(R/I)/(J/I)\cong R/J$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:R/I\to R/J$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(\overline{a})=\overline{a}$
\end_inset

.
 This is well-defined since if 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{a+x}$
\end_inset

 is another representative, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi(\overline{a+x}) & =\overline{a+x}\\
 & =\overline{a}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq J$
\end_inset

.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a surjective ring homomorphism with kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $J/I$
\end_inset

.
 So by the first isomorphism theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $(R/I)/(J/I)\cong R/J$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Show that the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+y^{2}=3z^{2}$
\end_inset

 has no solutions in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b,c)$
\end_inset

 is a solution.
 We can assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gcd}(a,b,c)=1$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+y^{2}-3z^{2}$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+y^{2}\equiv3z^{2}\mbox{ mod }n$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

.
 However when 
\begin_inset Formula $n=4$
\end_inset

, we run into a problem, since 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\equiv0\mbox{ mod }4$
\end_inset

 has no solutions where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Properties of Ideals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring with identity and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a nonempty subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
left ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle A\rangle_{\ell}=\bigcap_{\substack{I=\mbox{left ideal of }R\\
A\subseteq I
}
}I
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This is similarly defined for right ideals and two-sided ideals.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle A\rangle_{\ell}=RA=\{r_{1}a_{1}+\cdots+r_{n}a_{n}\mid n\in\mathbb{N},\,r_{i}\in R,\,a_{i}\in A\}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It is clear 
\begin_inset Formula $RA$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 We prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $RA$
\end_inset

 is a left ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}a_{1}+\cdots+r_{n}a_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}'a_{1}'+\cdots+r_{n}'a_{n}'$
\end_inset

 are two elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $RA$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{1}a_{1}+\cdots+r_{n}a_{n}-(r_{1}'a_{1}'+\cdots+r_{n}'a_{n}')=r_{1}a_{1}+\cdots+r_{n}a_{n}-r'a_{1}'-\cdots-r_{n}'a_{n}'\in RA
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $RA$
\end_inset

 is subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 under addtion.
 Next suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}a_{1}+\cdots+r_{n}a_{n}\in RA$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
r\cdot(r_{1}a_{1}+\cdots+r_{n}a_{n}) & =(rr_{1})a_{1}+\cdots+(rr_{n})a_{n}\in RA.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $RA$
\end_inset

 is closed under left scalar multiplication.
 Finally, the distributivity laws follow from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $RA$
\end_inset

 is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and shares the same addition and scalar multiplication action.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle A\rangle_{\ell}\subseteq RA$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we show 
\begin_inset Formula $RA\subseteq\langle A\rangle_{\ell}$
\end_inset

.
 To do this, we show for any left ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, that 
\begin_inset Formula $RA\subseteq I$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}a_{1}+\cdots+r_{n}a_{n}\in RA$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is an ideal which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}a_{i}\in I$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is closed under addition, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}a_{1}+\cdots+r_{n}a_{n}\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $RA\subseteq\langle A\rangle_{\ell}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $RA\supseteq\langle A\rangle_{\ell}$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $RA=\langle A\rangle_{\ell}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This is similarly proved for right ideals and two-sided ideals, using 
\begin_inset Formula $AR=\{a_{1}r_{1}+\cdots+a_{n}r_{n}\mid n\in\mathbb{N},\,r_{i}\in R,\,a_{i}\in A\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $RAR=\{r_{1}a_{1}s_{1}+\cdots+r_{n}a_{n}s_{n}\mid n\in\mathbb{N},\,r_{i},s_{i}\in R,\,a_{i}\in A\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{a\}$
\end_inset

, then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $Ra=\{ra\mid r\in R\}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
left principal ideal generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $aR=\{ar\mid r\in R\}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
right principal ideal generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $RaR=\{r_{1}as_{1}+\cdots+r_{n}as_{n}\mid r_{i},s_{i}\in R,\,n\in\mathbb{N}\}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
left principal ideal generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

, the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle2,x\rangle$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
principle.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 A proper ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
maximal 
\series default
if the only ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $m\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is maximal in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 Then every proper ideal is contained in some maximal ideal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring.
 A proper ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is maximal if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $R/\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime.
 We show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle p,x\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

 by showing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[x]/\langle p,x\rangle\cong\mathbb{Z}_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathbb{Z}[x]\to\mathbb{Z}_{p}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a_{0}+a_{1}x+\cdots+a_{n}x^{n})=\overline{a_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 We show 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a ring homomorphism.
 It is clearly additive, so we show it is multiplicative:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi((a_{0}+a_{1}x+\cdots+a_{n}x^{n})(b_{0}+b_{1}x+\cdots+b_{n}x^{n})) & =\varphi(a_{0}b_{0}+(a_{0}b_{1}+a_{1}b_{0})x+\cdots+(a_{0}b_{n}+\cdots+a_{n}b_{0})x^{n})\\
 & =\overline{a_{0}b_{0}}\\
 & =\overline{a_{0}}\overline{b_{0}}\\
 & =\varphi(a_{0}+a_{1}x+\cdots+a_{n}x^{n})\varphi(b_{0}+b_{1}x+\cdots+b_{n}x^{n})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the first isomorphism theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[x]/\mbox{Ker}\varphi\cong\mbox{Im}\varphi\cong\mathbb{Z}_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly the kernel is 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle2,x\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 Denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Max}(R)=\{\mathfrak{m}\mid\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R\}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]/\langle x\rangle\cong R$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring.
 An ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
prime 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\neq R$
\end_inset

 and if whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, then either 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Spec}(R)=\{\mathfrak{p}\mid\mathfrak{p}\mbox{ is a prime ideal in }R\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The prime ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle0\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle p\rangle$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a prime number.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring.
 Then an ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is prime if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $R/\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{a},\overline{b}\in R/\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 such 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{ab}=\overline{0}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, which implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, which is exactly the same as saying either 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{a}=\overline{0}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{b}=\overline{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $R/\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{ab}=0$
\end_inset

 implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{a}=\overline{0}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{b}=\overline{0}$
\end_inset

, which is the same as saying either 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Maximal ideals are prime ideals.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
local ring 
\series default
if it has a unique maximal ideal.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring.
 The following statements are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a local ring.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $1+x\in R^{\times}$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in R\setminus R^{\times}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(1)\implies(2)$
\end_inset

: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}\in\mbox{Max}(R)$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in R\setminus R^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

 must be contained in a maximal ideal, and the only one available is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+x)\neq R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $1+x\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 by the same argument.
 But then 
\begin_inset Formula $1=x-(1+x)\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 which is a contradiction.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $1+x$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(2)\implies(1):$
\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m'}$
\end_inset

 are maximal ideals such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m\neq m'}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}\subset\mathfrak{m}+\mathfrak{m'}\subset R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}\neq\mathfrak{m'}$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}+\mathfrak{m'}=R$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $1=a+b$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\mathfrak{m'}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1-b$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $b\notin R^{\times}$
\end_inset

, but that would make 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R^{\times}$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Integral Domains
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring.
 An element 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
zerodivisor 
\series default
if there exists a nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=0$
\end_inset

.
 If there does not exist a nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=0$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
nonzerodivisor
\series default
.
 If every nonzero element in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a nonzerodivisor, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an 
\series bold
integral domain
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The ring of integers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every field is an integral domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is prime and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x},\overline{y}\in R\slash I$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}\overline{y}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $xy\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is prime, we either have 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in I$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, either 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{y}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $xy\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}\overline{y}=0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain, we either have 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{y}=0$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, either 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A finite integral domain is a field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R\setminus\{0\}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon R\to R$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(x)=ax
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is finite, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is bijective.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(b)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is a multiplicative inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Euclidean Domains
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}=\{0,1,2,\dots\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An integral domain 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
Euclidean 
\series default
if there is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}\colon R\backslash\{0\}\to\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 has division with remainder with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

: for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq0$
\end_inset

 we can find 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a=bq+r,\qquad r=0\text{ or }\mathrm{d}(r)<\mathrm{d}(b).\label{eq:euclideanfunction}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We allow 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

 in this definition since in that case we can use 
\begin_inset Formula $q=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

.
 A function satisfying 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:euclideanfunction})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
Euclidean function
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean domain with respect to the Euclidean function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}\colon K\backslash\{0\}\to\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}(x)=0
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in K$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq0$
\end_inset

, then we set 
\begin_inset Formula $q=ab^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The ring of integers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean Domain with respect to the Euclidean function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}\colon\mathbb{Z}\backslash\{0\}\to\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}(m)=|m|
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $|a|<|b|$
\end_inset

, then we set 
\begin_inset Formula $q=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r=a$
\end_inset

, so assume 
\begin_inset Formula $|a|>|b|$
\end_inset

.
 Without loss of generality, assume both 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are positive.
 Then there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
bq\leq a<b(q+1).
\]

\end_inset

Choose such a 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and set 
\begin_inset Formula $r=a-bq$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $bq=a$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

, otherwise
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
|r| & =|a-bq|\\
 & <|b(q+1)-bq|\\
 & =|b(q+1-q)|\\
 & =|b|.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x]$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean Domain with respect to the Euclidean function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}\colon K[x]\backslash\{0\}\to\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}(f(x))=\deg f(x)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in K[x]\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Euclidean Algorithm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
divides 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, written 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid b$
\end_inset

, if there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ac=b$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
An element 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in R$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gcd}(a,b)$
\end_inset

 if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $d'\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $d'\mid a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d'\mid b$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid d'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a Euclidean domain and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a & =bq+r & N(r)<N(b)\mbox{ or }r=0\\
b & =rq_{0}+r_{0} & N(r_{0})<N(r)\mbox{ or }r=0\\
r & =r_{0}q_{1}+r_{1} & N(r_{1})<N(r_{0})\mbox{ or }r=0\\
 & \vdots & \vdots\\
r_{n-1} & =r_{n}q_{n+1} & N(r_{n})<N(b)\mbox{ or }r=0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $r\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

, we get a strictly descending sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N(b)>N(r)>N(r_{0})>N(r_{1})>\cdots>N(r_{n})
\]

\end_inset

This algorithm must terminate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The last nonzero remainder in the division algorithm for 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is the a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gcd}(a,b)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean Domain, then every ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is principle.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle0\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I\neq0$
\end_inset

, then let 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in I-\{0\}$
\end_inset

 be an element of minimal norm.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $N(d)=\mbox{min}\{N(a)\mid a\in I-\{0\}\}$
\end_inset

.
 We show 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle d\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle d\rangle\subset I$
\end_inset

.
 To show the converse, let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean domain, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $a=dq+r$
\end_inset

 where either 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $N(r)<N(d)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in I$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $r=a-dq\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $N(d)$
\end_inset

 is minimal, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $a=dq\in\langle d\rangle$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle d\rangle\supset I$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
a PID since 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle2,x\rangle$
\end_inset

 is not a principal ideal, so it can't be a Euclidean Domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[\sqrt{-5}]$
\end_inset

 is not a Euclidean Domain since it's not even a principal ideal: 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle3,1+\sqrt{-5}\rangle$
\end_inset

 is not principle.
 However 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[\sqrt{-5}]$
\end_inset

 does have a positive multiplicative norm, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $N(a+b\sqrt{-5})=a^{2}+5b^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an Integral Domain and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R-\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a,b\rangle=\langle d\rangle$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is a greatest common divisor of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a,b\rangle=\langle d\rangle$
\end_inset

, there is 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $dx=a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $dy=b$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is a common divisor of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $d'$
\end_inset

 be another common divisor of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 Then there is 
\begin_inset Formula $x',y'\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $d'x'=a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d'y'=b$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a,b\rangle=\langle d\rangle$
\end_inset

, there is 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $d=au+bv$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $d=(d'x')u+(d'y')v=d'(x'u+y'v)$
\end_inset

, do 
\begin_inset Formula $d'\mid d$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an Integral Domain and let 
\begin_inset Formula $d,d'\in R-\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle d\rangle=\langle d'\rangle$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $d'=du$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Principal Ideal Domain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An Integral Domain 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
Principal Ideal Domain (PID) 
\series default
if every ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is principal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Euclidean Domains are Principal Ideal Domains, but Principal Ideal Domains
 do not have to be Euclidean Domains.
 For example, the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\left[\frac{1+\sqrt{-19}}{2}\right]$
\end_inset

 is a PID but not an ED.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a PID and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R-\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle d\rangle=\langle a,b\rangle$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gcd}(a,b)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a PID.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\mbox{Spec}R-\{0\}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is principal, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=\langle p\rangle$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in R-\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a ring with identity, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}\in\mbox{Max}R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}\subset\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a PID, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is a principal ideal, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=(m)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $p=mr$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in R$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $mr\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, which implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $r=pq$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p=mpq$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $p(1-mq)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p\neq0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an Integral Domain, 
\begin_inset Formula $mq=1$
\end_inset

.
 But this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is a unit, which is a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a PID.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 is a PID if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a field, then 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 is an ED, and therefore a PID.
 Now assume 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 is a PID.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]/\langle x\rangle\cong R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 is a PID, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal, and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an Integral Domain.
 A positive norm 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
Dedekind-Hasse Norm
\series default
 if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R-\{0\}$
\end_inset

, either 
\begin_inset Formula $b\mid a$
\end_inset

 or there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in\langle a,b\rangle-\{0\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $0<N(r)<N(b)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an Integral Domain.
 If there is a Dedekind-Hasse norm 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a PID.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I=0$
\end_inset

, then we are done.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I\neq0$
\end_inset

, then let 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in I-\{0\}$
\end_inset

 be an element of minimal norm.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle b\rangle\subset I$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in I-\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then either 
\begin_inset Formula $b\mid a$
\end_inset

 or there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $r=xa-bq$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $N(r)<N(b)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in I-\{0\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N(r)>N(b)$
\end_inset

 which is a contradiction.
  
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Unique Factorization Domains
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an Integral Domain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A nonzero element 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in R-R^{\times}$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
irreducible
\series default
 if whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $r=ab$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

, then either 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R^{\times}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in R^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is not irreducible, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
reducible
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an Integral Domain.
 A nonzero element 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in R$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
prime 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle p\rangle$
\end_inset

 is prime.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Two nonzero elements 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

 are said to be 
\series bold
associate 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $b=au$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in R^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{primeisirreducible}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an Integral Domain.
 Then every prime is irreducible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime element in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p=ab$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

, then either 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid a$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid b$
\end_inset

.
 Without loss of generality, assume 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid a$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $a=pq$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(pq)b$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $p(1-qb)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\neq0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $bq=1$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The converse to 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{primeisirreducible})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
always true.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Take 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\mathbb{Z}[\sqrt{-5}]$
\end_inset

.
 We will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[\sqrt{-5}]$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 is not prime.
 Recall the norm 
\begin_inset Formula $N:\mathbb{Z}[\sqrt{-5}]\to\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $N(a+b\sqrt{-5})=a^{2}+5b^{2}$
\end_inset

, is multiplicative.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $3=\alpha\beta$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta\in\mathbb{Z}[\sqrt{-5}]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $N(3)=N(\alpha)N(\beta)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $9=N(\alpha)N(\beta)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\alpha)=9$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\beta)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\beta)=9$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\alpha)=1$
\end_inset

.
 So assume 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\alpha)=N(\beta)=3$
\end_inset

.
 But this is impossible since there are no integers 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}+5b^{2}=3$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 is not prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[\sqrt{-5}]$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid(2+\sqrt{-5})(2-\sqrt{-5})$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $3\not\mid(2+\sqrt{-5})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $3\not\mid(2-\sqrt{-5})$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a PID.
 A nonzero element is prime if and only if it is irreducible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 From 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{primeisirreducible})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we know that being prime implies being irreducible.
 So it suffices to check the converse.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible element in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle r\rangle\subset\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 for some maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a PID, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\langle m\rangle$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle r\rangle$
\end_inset

, there is some 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $r=mq$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is irreducible and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is not a unit, 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 must be a unit, so 
\begin_inset Formula $qu=1$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $m=ru$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle r\rangle$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\langle r\rangle$
\end_inset

.
  
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an integral domain.
 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
Unique Factorization Domain (UFD)
\series default
 if every nonzero nonunit element 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in R$
\end_inset

 has the following two properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 can be written as a product of irreducibles 
\begin_inset Formula $r=p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{m}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1},p_{2},\dots,p_{m}$
\end_inset

 are irreducible elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
This decomposition is unique up to associates, i.e.
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $r=p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{m}=q_{1}q_{2}\cdots q_{\ell}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i},q_{j}$
\end_inset

 are all irreducible elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $m=\ell$
\end_inset

 and (perhaps after reordering the factors) 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}\sim q_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is a UFD.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every field is a UFD.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a PID, then every ascending chain of ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{1}\subset I_{2}\subset I_{3}\subset\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
terminates, i.e.
 there is some 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq1$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{k}=I_{k+1}=I_{k+2}=\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $J=\bigcup_{n\geq1}I_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Let's check that 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 is an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in J$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I_{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in I_{n}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n$
\end_inset

.
 Assume without loss of generality that 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq m$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in I_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is an ideal, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $ax+y\in I_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $ax+y\in J$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a PID, 
\begin_inset Formula $J=\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in R$
\end_inset

.
 There there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq1$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x\rangle\subset I_{k}\subset I_{k+1}\subset\cdots\subset J=\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

 forces 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{k}=I_{k+1}=\cdots=J$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every PID is a UFD.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a PID and let 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero nonunit element in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is irreducible, then we are done.
 If not, then we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $r=r_{1}r_{2}$
\end_inset

 where neither 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 nor 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 If both 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 are irreducible, then we are done.
 Otherwise at least one of them, say 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

, is reducible so we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}=r_{11}r_{12}$
\end_inset

 with neither being a unit.
 This process terminates after finitely many steps because otherwise we'd
 have an ascending chain of ideals 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle r\rangle\subset\langle r_{1}\rangle\subset\langle r_{11}\rangle\subset\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This gives a contradiction.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $r=p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{m}$
\end_inset

 with all 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 being irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $r=p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{m}=q_{1}q_{2}\cdots q_{\ell}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

 irreducible.
 We will show 
\begin_inset Formula $m=\ell$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}\sim q_{i}$
\end_inset

 (perhaps after reordering) by induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r=p_{1}=q_{1}q_{2}\cdots q_{\ell}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 is prime, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}\mid q_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}u=q_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 are irreducible, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 be a unit.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In a UFD 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, a nonzero element is prime if and only if it is irreducible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Prime implies irreducible in any integral domain.
 Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero irreducible element in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Let also 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 be nonzero elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $r\mid ab$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=rc$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a UFD, 
\begin_inset Formula $a=p_{1}\cdots p_{m}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b=q_{1}\cdots q_{\ell}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $c=s_{1}\cdots s_{t}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i},q_{j},s_{k}$
\end_inset

 all irreducible.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{1}\cdots p_{m}q_{1}\cdots q_{\ell}=rs_{1}\cdots s_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
implies 
\begin_inset Formula $r\sim p_{i}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $r\sim q_{j}$
\end_inset

, which means 
\begin_inset Formula $r\mid a$
\end_inset

 in the first case or 
\begin_inset Formula $r\mid b$
\end_inset

 in the second case.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is a prime.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a UFD and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R-\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $a=up_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}p_{2}^{\alpha_{2}}\cdots p_{m}^{\alpha_{m}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b=vp_{1}^{\beta_{1}}p_{2}^{\beta_{2}}\cdots p_{m}^{\beta_{m}}$
\end_inset

 are the prime factorizations of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in R^{\times}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 irreducible, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i},\beta_{i}\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $d=p_{1}^{\mu_{1}}p_{2}^{\mu_{2}}\cdots p_{m}^{\mu_{m}}$
\end_inset

 is a greatest common divisor of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{i}=\mbox{min}(\alpha_{i},\beta_{i})$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{i}=\mbox{min}(\alpha_{i},\beta_{i})$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}^{\mu_{i}}$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}^{\alpha_{i}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}^{\beta_{i}}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $d=p_{1}^{\mu_{1}}p_{2}^{\mu_{2}}\cdots p_{m}^{\mu_{m}}$
\end_inset

 divides both 
\begin_inset Formula $a=up_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}p_{2}^{\alpha_{2}}\cdots p_{m}^{\alpha_{m}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b=up_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}p_{2}^{\alpha_{2}}\cdots p_{m}^{\alpha_{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in R$
\end_inset

 be a common divisor for 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a UFD, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $c=q_{1}^{\delta_{1}}q_{2}^{\delta_{2}}\cdots q_{\ell}^{\delta_{\ell}}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 irreducible and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{i}\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}\mid p_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}\cdots p_{m}^{\alpha_{m}}$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq j\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}$
\end_inset

 are both irreducible and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}$
\end_inset

, they must be associate.
 Similarly, perhaps after reordering, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[2i]$
\end_inset

 is not a UFD since 
\begin_inset Formula $-4=-2\cdot2=2i\cdot2i$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2i$
\end_inset

 are not associate in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[2i]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Factorization in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[i]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We want to find the irreducibles in ring of Gaussian integers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[i]$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $N:\mathbb{Z}[i]\to\mathbb{N}\cup\{0\}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $N(a+bi)=a^{2}+b^{2}$
\end_inset

 is a positive, multiplicative norm.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{Z}[i]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\alpha)=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 is prime, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is prime, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\alpha\rangle\cap\mathbb{Z}=\langle N(\alpha)\rangle$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p=a^{2}+b^{2}$
\end_inset

 for some integers 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(a+ib)(a-ib)=N(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=a+ib$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 be an odd prime.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid n^{2}+1$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $p\equiv1\mbox{ mod }4$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is prime and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\equiv1\mbox{ mod }4$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is reducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[i]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Rings of Fractions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In this section, let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a nonempty subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
multiplicative system 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $0\notin S$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 does not contain any zero divisors, and is closed under multiplication.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Take 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\mathbb{Z}\setminus\{0\}$
\end_inset

 is a multiplicative system.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain, then 
\begin_inset Formula $R\setminus\{0\}$
\end_inset

 is a multiplicative system because 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle0\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $R\times S$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $(r,s)\sim(r',s')$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $rs'=r's$
\end_inset

.
 We denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{r}{s}$
\end_inset

 the equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $(r,s)$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 and we denote 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S^{-1}R=\left\{ \frac{r}{s}\mid r\in R,\,s\in S\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdot$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{-1}R$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{r_{1}}{s_{1}}+\frac{r_{2}}{s_{2}}=\frac{s_{2}r_{1}+s_{1}r_{2}}{s_{1}s_{2}}\qquad\frac{r_{1}}{s_{1}}\frac{r_{2}}{s_{2}}=\frac{r_{1}r_{2}}{s_{1}s_{2}},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1},r_{2}\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1},s_{2}\in S$
\end_inset

.
 Check that this is well-defined.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring (which doesn't necessarily contain identity) and
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a multiplicative system in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $S^{-1}R$
\end_inset

 is a commutative ring with identity that contains an isomorphic copy of
 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that every 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{-1}R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain and if 
\begin_inset Formula $S=R\setminus\{0\}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{-1}R$
\end_inset

 is a field and is called the 
\series bold
field of fractions 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First we check that 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{-1}R$
\end_inset

 is abelian group.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1},r_{2},r_{3}\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1},s_{2},s_{3}\in S$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(\frac{r_{1}}{s_{1}}+\frac{r_{2}}{s_{2}}\right)+\frac{r_{3}}{s_{3}} & =\frac{s_{2}r_{1}+s_{1}r_{2}}{s_{1}s_{2}}+\frac{r_{3}}{s_{3}}\\
 & =\frac{s_{3}(s_{2}r_{1}+s_{1}r_{2})+r_{3}(s_{1}s_{2})}{(s_{1}s_{2})s_{3}}\\
 & =\frac{r_{1}(s_{2}s_{3})+s_{1}(s_{3}r_{2}+s_{2}r_{3})}{s_{1}(s_{2}s_{3})}\\
 & =\frac{r_{1}}{s_{1}}+\frac{s_{3}r_{2}+s_{2}r_{3}}{s_{2}s_{3}}\\
 & =\frac{r_{1}}{s_{1}}+\left(\frac{r_{2}}{s_{2}}+\frac{r_{3}}{s_{3}}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similary calculations show it is associative and commutative.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:R\to S^{-1}R$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(r)=\frac{rs}{s},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a ring homomorphism with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi=\{0\}$
\end_inset

, therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $R\cong\varphi(R)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Chinese Remainder Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 be ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 are 
\series bold
relatively prime 
\series default
to one another if 
\begin_inset Formula $I+J=R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In other words, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in J$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x+y=1$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I=a\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J=b\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gcd}(a,b)=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1},\dots,I_{k}$
\end_inset

 be pairwise relatively prime 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime, then 
\begin_inset Formula $I\cap J=IJ$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1},\dots,I_{k}$
\end_inset

 are pairwise relatively prime (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{i}+I_{j}=R$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

), then 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}\cdots I_{k}=I_{1}\cap\cdots\cap I_{k}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 The inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $IJ\subset I\cap J$
\end_inset

 holds in every ring.
 For the reverse inclusion, note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
I\cap J & =(I\cap J)(I+J)\\
 & \subset IJ.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 We prove by induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 The base case is (1).
 Now suppose the statement is true for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k-1\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1},\dots I_{k-1}$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime to 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{k}$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in I_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}\in I_{k}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}+y_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i<k$
\end_inset

.
 Choose such 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in I_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}\in I_{k}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i<k$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
1 & =(x_{1}+y_{1})\cdots(x_{k-1}+y_{k-1})\\
 & \in I_{1}\cdots I_{k-1}+I_{k}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}\cdots I_{k-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{k}$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime.
 Therefore using the base case and induction step, we see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
I_{1}\cap\cdots\cap I_{k} & =(I_{1}\cdots I_{k-1})\cap I_{k}\\
 & =I_{1}\cdots I_{k}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (The Chinese Remainder Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1},\dots,I_{k}$
\end_inset

 be pairwise relatively prime ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R\slash I_{1}\cdots I_{k}\cong R\slash I_{1}\times\cdots\times R\slash I_{k}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon R\to R\slash I_{1}\times\cdots\times R\slash I_{k}$
\end_inset

 be the ring homomorphism given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(r)=(r+I_{1},\dots,r+I_{k})
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in R$
\end_inset

.
 We first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(r_{1}+I_{1},\dots,r_{k}+I_{k})\in R\slash I_{1}\times\cdots\times R\slash I_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1},\dots,I_{k}$
\end_inset

 are pairwise relatively prime, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i<j\leq k$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{ij}\in I_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{ji}\in I_{j}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{ij}+x_{ji}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r:=\sum_{j=1}^{k}r_{j}x_{1j}\cdots\widehat{x}_{jj}\cdots x_{kj}\in R,
\]

\end_inset

where the hat symbol means omit that element.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(r)=(r_{1}+I_{1},\dots,r_{k}+I_{k})$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, since 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{ij}\equiv1\text{ mod }I_{j}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 fixed and 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $r\text{ mod }I_{j}\equiv r_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next, observe that the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}\cdots I_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(r)=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $r+I_{j}=I_{j}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\dots,k$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in I_{1}\cap\cdots\cap I_{k}=I_{1}\cdots I_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 The theorem now follows from the first isomorphism theorem for rings.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Polynomial Rings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that when 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an ID, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{deg}(f(x)g(x))=\mbox{deg}(f(x))+\mbox{deg}(g(x))$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an I.D.
 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I[x]=\left\{ f(x)\in R[x]\mid\mbox{all coefficients of }f(x)\mbox{ are in }I.\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $I[x]$
\end_inset

 is an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R[x]/I[x]\cong(R/I)[x].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $I\in\mbox{Spec}R$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $I[x]\in\mbox{Spec}(R[x])$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Define a ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:R[x]\to(R/I)[x]$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a_{0}+a_{1}x+\cdots+a_{n}x^{n})=\overline{a_{0}}x+\overline{a_{1}}x^{2}+\cdots+\overline{a_{n}}x^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $I[x]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I\in\mbox{Spec}R$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]/I[x]\cong(R/I)[x]$
\end_inset

 is an Integral Domain, so 
\begin_inset Formula $I[x]\in\mbox{Spec}R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Polynomial Rings that are UFDs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 is irreducible when 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=g(x)h(x)$
\end_inset

 implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 is a unit or 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 Another way to think of this is that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible if it factors as 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=g(x)h(x)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq\mbox{deg}(g(x))<\mbox{deg}(f(x))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq\mbox{deg}(h(x))<\mbox{deg}(f(x))$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 is a UFD if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a UFD.
 To show this, we need Gauss' Lemma:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Gauss Lemma) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a UFD and let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be its field of fractions.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=A(x)B(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $A(x),B(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{deg}(A(x)),\mbox{deg}(B(x))\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 There is some 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $df(x)=a'(x)b'(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a'(x),b'(x)\in R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a UFD, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $d=p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 being irreducible.
 Now since 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 is prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 is prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 too.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{m}f(x)=a'(x)b'(x)\qquad\mbox{in }R[x]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}\mid a'(x)b'(x)$
\end_inset

 together with 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 being a prime implies 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 divides one of 
\begin_inset Formula $a'(x)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b'(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Say 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $a'(x)$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $a'(x)=p_{1}a''(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a''(x)\in R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{n}f(x)=p_{1}a''(x)b'(x).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And since we are in an integral domain, we can cancel 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 on both sides.
 The proceeding inductively, we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a UFD and let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be its field of fractions.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in R[x]$
\end_inset

 be such that the gcd of the coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\implies)$
\end_inset

 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Then by Gauss' Lemma, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(\impliedby)$
\end_inset

 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=a(x)b(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a(x),b(x)\in R[x]\subset F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

, one of the factors, say 
\begin_inset Formula $a(x)$
\end_inset

, has to a constant; 
\begin_inset Formula $a(x)=r\in R$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=rb(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in R$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 divides all of the coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 is a UFD if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a UFD.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\impliedby)$
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero nonunit element in 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 be the gcd of the coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=dp(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\in R[x]$
\end_inset

 and such that the gcd of the coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a UFD, 
\begin_inset Formula $d=q_{1}q_{2}\cdots q_{t}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, so they are also prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 So it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 is a finite product of irreducibles in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

 is a UFD, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=p_{1}'(x)\cdots p_{n}'(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}'(x)$
\end_inset

 irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 By Gauss' Lemma, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=p_{1}(x)\cdots p_{n}(x)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(x)=a_{i}p_{i}'(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}'(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(x)\mid p(x)$
\end_inset

, the gcd of the coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We need to show uniqueness.
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 be such that the gcd of all coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=p_{1}(x)\cdots p_{n}(x)=\ell_{1}(x)\cdots\ell_{s}(x)$
\end_inset

 are two factorizations into irreducibles in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]\subseteq F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $n=s$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(x)\sim\ell_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

 is a UFD.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}p_{i}(x)=a_{i}\ell_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i},b_{i}\in R$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 So gcd of LHS is the same as the gcd of the RHS which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}=b_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(x)\sim\ell_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(\implies)$
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero nonunit element in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in R[x]$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $r=p_{1}(x)\cdots p_{n}(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 be irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 But the the degree on the left side must be equal to the degree of the
 right hand side.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{deg}(p_{i}(x))=0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(x)=p_{i}\in R$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Uniqueness holds because 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 is a UFD and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Irreducibility Criteria
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{rootfactor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 has a factor of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 has a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 there is some 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in F$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\implies)$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=(ax+b)g(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in F$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=-ab^{-1}\in F$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(\impliedby)$
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in F$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=(x-\alpha)g(x)+r(x)
\]

\end_inset

where either 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{deg}r(x)<1$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=r\in F$
\end_inset

 is a constant.
 And this is a contradiciton since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(\alpha) & =(\alpha-\alpha)g(\alpha)+r(\alpha)\\
 & =r,
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=(x-\alpha)g(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{rootdeg2}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 be a polynomial of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 has a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\impliedby)$
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 has a root 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in F$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=(x-\alpha)g(x)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(\implies)$
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=g(x)h(x)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x),h(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{deg}g(x)+\mbox{deg}h(x)=\mbox{deg}f(x)\leq3
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)$
\end_inset

 has degree 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{rootfactor})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 must have a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{rovers}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=a_{n}x^{n}+a_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{1}x+a_{0}\in\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r/s\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gcd}(r,s)=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $r\mid a_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s\mid a_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $r/s$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =f\left(\frac{r}{s}\right)\\
 & =a_{n}\left(\frac{r}{s}\right)^{n}+a_{n-1}\left(\frac{r}{s}\right)^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{1}\left(\frac{r}{s}\right)+a_{0}\\
 & =\frac{a_{n}r^{n}+a_{n-1}sr^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{1}s^{n-1}r+a_{0}s^{n}}{s^{n}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r(a_{n}r^{n-1}+a_{n-1}sr^{n-2}+\cdots+a_{1}s^{n-1})=-a_{0}s^{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $r\mid a_{0}s^{n}$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime, 
\begin_inset Formula $r\mid a_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s(a_{n-1}r^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{1}s^{n-2}r+a_{0}s^{n-1})=-a_{n}r^{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $s\mid a_{n}$
\end_inset

 by the same reasoning as above.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{exampleroot}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{3}+x^{2}+1\in\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

.
 By Gauss' Lemma, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}[x]$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{rootdeg2})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 has a root 
\begin_inset Formula $r/s\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{rovers})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s\mid1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r\mid1$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $r/s=\pm1$
\end_inset

.
 However 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\pm1)\neq0$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime.
 We show 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{3}-p\in\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Using the same reasoning as in the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Example~(
\backslash
ref{exampleroot})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, the only possible roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{3}-p$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

, however none of these are roots.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Eisenstein's Criterion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an Integral Domain and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 be a prime ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{n}+c_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\cdots+c_{1}x+c_{0}$
\end_inset

 be a polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq1\leq n-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}\notin\mathfrak{p}^{2}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible: 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=a(x)b(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a(x),b(x)\in R[x]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{deg}a(x),\mbox{deg}b(x)\geq1$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a(x)=a_{0}+a_{1}x+\cdots+a_{k}x^{k}\qquad\mbox{and}\qquad b(x)=b_{0}+b_{1}x+\cdots+b_{\ell}x^{\ell}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{a_{0}b_{0}}=\overline{0}$
\end_inset

 modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{a_{0}}=\overline{0}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{b_{0}}=\overline{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{a_{0}}=\overline{0}$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{b_{0}}\neq\overline{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{a_{0}b_{1}+a_{1}b_{0}}=\overline{0}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{a_{1}b_{0}}=\overline{0}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{a_{1}}=\overline{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Continuing this algorthim, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{a_{0}}=\overline{a_{1}}=\cdots=\overline{a_{k}}=\overline{0}$
\end_inset

.
 But we obtain a contradiction since 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{a_{k}b_{k}}=\overline{1}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{a_{0}}=\overline{b_{0}}=\overline{0}$
\end_inset

, and this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}=a_{0}b_{0}\in\mathfrak{p}^{2}$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Eisenstein's Criterion for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{n}+a_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{1}x+a_{0}$
\end_inset

 be a polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid a_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq1\leq n-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2}\not\mid a_{0}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{5}-30x^{4}+9x^{3}-6x+3$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

 by Eisenstein's Criterion for 
\begin_inset Formula $p=3$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{4}+1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x+1)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x+1)=x^{4}+4x^{3}+6x^{2}+4x+2$
\end_inset

 is Eisenstein at 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x+1)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Field Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Field Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall that a field 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a commutative ring with identity such that every nonzero element in
 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 has an inverse.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field.
 The 
\series bold
characteristic 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}F$
\end_inset

, is the smallest positive integer such that 
\begin_inset Formula $n\cdot1_{F}=0$
\end_inset

.
 If such an integer doesn't exist, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}F=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}\mathbb{Q}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}\mathbb{F}_{p}=p$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The characteristic of a field 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is either 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 or a prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}F=0$
\end_inset

 then we are done, so assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}F=m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is not prime.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $m=ab$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b>1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $m\cdot1_{F}=(a\cdot1_{F})(b\cdot1_{F})=0$
\end_inset

 implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $(a\cdot1_{F})=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $(b\cdot1_{F})=0$
\end_inset

.
 In either case, we get a contradiction since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}F\leq a,b<m$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field and define 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathbb{Z}\to F$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(n)=n\cdot1_{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a ring homomorphism.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/\mbox{Ker}\varphi\cong\varphi(\mathbb{Z})\subseteq F$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is a PID, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi=m\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\mbox{ch}F$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in m\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $m=p$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(1)=0$
\end_inset

 which is a contradiction, so 
\begin_inset Formula $m=p$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi=p\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}\cong\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}\subseteq F$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}F=0$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\cong\varphi(\mathbb{Z})\subseteq F$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 contains an isomorphic copy of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 In either case, we call this the 
\series bold
prime subfield 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Field Extension) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be fields.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a subfield of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
field extension 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subset K$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $K/F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 is a field extension, then 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a vector space over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
degree 
\series default
of the extension 
\begin_inset Formula $K/F$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $[K:F]$
\end_inset

, is the dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathbb{R}:\mathbb{R}]=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathbb{C}:\mathbb{R}]=2$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a field and 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 is an irreducible polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, can we find a field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 such that the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=0$
\end_inset

 has a solution in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

? Yes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Then there is a field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 containing (an isomorphic copy of) 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 has a root 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Identifying 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 with this isomorphic copy which is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, we'll regard 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 as a field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

, which is a PID, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle p(x)\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $K:=F[x]/\langle p(x)\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:F[x]\to F[x]/\langle p(x)\rangle$
\end_inset

 be the canonical projection map given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(a(x))=\overline{a(x)}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:=\pi_{_{\mid F}}$
\end_inset

 gives a ring homomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]/\langle p(x)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a field and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(1)\neq0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi=0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Finally, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha:=\overline{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p(\alpha) & =p(\overline{x})\\
 & =\overline{p(x)}\\
 & =\overline{0}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field, 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K:=F[x]/\langle p(x)\rangle$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha:=\bar{x}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\mbox{deg}p(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,\alpha,\dots,\alpha^{n-1}\}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

-basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $[K:F]=n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g(x)}\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a field, 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean Domain, so there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x),r(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=q(x)p(x)+r(x)$
\end_inset

 with either 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{deg}r(x)\leq n-1$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g(x)}=\bar{0}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=c_{0}+c_{1}x+\cdots+c_{\ell}x^{\ell}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\leq n-1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{g(x)} & =\overline{q(x)p(x)+r(x)}\\
 & =\overline{r(x)}\\
 & =\overline{c_{0}+c_{1}x+\cdots+c_{\ell}x^{\ell}}\\
 & =c_{0}+c_{1}\alpha+\cdots+c_{\ell}\alpha^{\ell}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)\in\mbox{Span}\{1,\alpha,\dots,\alpha^{n-1}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,\alpha,\dots,\alpha^{n-1}\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0},b_{1},\dots,b_{n-1}\in F$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}+b_{1}\alpha+\cdots+b_{n-1}\alpha^{n-1}=\bar{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}+b_{1}x+\cdots+b_{n-1}x^{n-1}=p(x)q(x)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 But the degree of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, so we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x)=0$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n-1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Algebraic Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K/F$
\end_inset

 be a field extension.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
An element 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
algebraic 
\series default
over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 if there exists a nonzero polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Otherwise, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
transcendental
\series default
 over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $K/F$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
algebraic 
\series default
if every 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\pi)=0$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x-\pi$
\end_inset

.
 However, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is transcendental over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(i)=0$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{2}+1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K/F$
\end_inset

 be a field extension.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, then there is a unique monic irreducible polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 as a root, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\mid f(x)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 be a polynomial of minimal degree having 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 as a root.
 We can assume, without loss of generality, that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 is monic.
 We show that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose not.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=a(x)b(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a(x),b(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq\mbox{deg}a(x)<\mbox{deg}p(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq\mbox{deg}b(x)<\mbox{deg}p(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $0=p(\alpha)=a(\alpha)b(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $a(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 But this contradicts the minimality of the degree of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Next, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean Domain, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x),r(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=q(x)p(x)+r(x)$
\end_inset

 where either 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{deg}r(x)<\mbox{deg}p(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $r(\alpha)=f(\alpha)-q(\alpha)p(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 But this contradicts the minimality of the degree of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall that if 
\begin_inset Formula $K/F$
\end_inset

 is a field extension, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq F(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 In this case, the degree of the extension 
\begin_inset Formula $[F(\alpha):F]$
\end_inset

 is the degree of the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K\subseteq L$
\end_inset

 are field extensions, then 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:F]=[L:K][K:F]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $[K:F]=\ell$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]=m$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{m}\}$
\end_inset

 be a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\beta_{1},\dots,\beta_{\ell}\}$
\end_inset

 be a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\alpha_{1}\beta_{1},\dots,\alpha_{m}\beta_{\ell}\}$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=x^{3}+3x-1$
\end_inset

 is irreducible over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\pm1)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 But there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Let's show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}\notin\mathbb{Q}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}\in\mathbb{Q}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\subseteq\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2})\subseteq\mathbb{Q}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $3=[\mathbb{Q}(\alpha):\mathbb{Q}]=[\mathbb{Q}(\alpha):\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2})][\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2}):\mathbb{Q}]=[\mathbb{Q}(\alpha):\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2})]\cdot2$
\end_inset

 which is a contradiction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 be a field extension and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{\ell})=F(\alpha_{1})(\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell})=\cdots=F(\alpha_{1})(\alpha_{2})\cdots(\alpha_{\ell}).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 be a field extension.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}\in K$
\end_inset

 are all algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq F(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{\ell})$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}=\mbox{deg}m_{\alpha_{i},F}$
\end_inset

.
 We have a sequence of field extensions
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F\subseteq F(\alpha_{1})\subseteq F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2})\subseteq\cdots\subseteq F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}):F] & =[F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}):F(\alpha_{1})][F(\alpha_{1}):F]\\
 & =[F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}):F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2})][F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2}):F(\alpha_{1})][F(\alpha_{1}):F]\\
 & =[F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}):F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots\alpha_{\ell-1})]\cdots[F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2}):F(\alpha_{1})][F(\alpha_{1}):F]\\
 & \leq n_{\ell}\cdots n_{2}n_{1}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 be a field extension.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 is finite if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $K=F(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{\ell})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Algebraically Closed Field and Algebraic Closure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop5}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For any field 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, there is an algebraically closed field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For each nonconstant monic 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{f}$
\end_inset

 denote a variable.
 Consider the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $E=F[\dots,X_{f},\dots]$
\end_inset

 and the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\{f(X_{f})\mid f\mbox{ is nonconstant monic polynomial}\}$
\end_inset

.
 We check that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal.
 Suppose not.
 Then there exists nonconstant monic polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},\dots,g_{n}\in F[\dots,X_{f},\dots]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $1=g_{1}f_{1}(X_{f_{1}})+\cdots+g_{n}f_{n}(X_{f_{n}})$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{f_{i}}=\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $1=0$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal, it is contained in a maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1}=E/\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is a field that contains 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and every 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 has a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}_{f}$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Now continue this process with 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1}$
\end_inset

, etc...
 We obtain an ascending chain of fields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=K_{0}\subseteq K_{1}\subseteq K_{2}\subseteq\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in K_{i}[x]$
\end_inset

 has a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{i+1}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\bigcup_{i=0}^{\infty}K_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a field which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is algebraically closed: If 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in K[x]$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in K_{i}[x]$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i\geq0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{i+1}\subseteq K$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop6}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be an algebraically closed field containing 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{F}=\{\alpha\in K\mid\alpha$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $F\}$
\end_inset

 is an algebraic closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{F}$
\end_inset

 is a subfield of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

: If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta\in\bar{F}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subset F(\alpha,\beta)$
\end_inset

 is finite, hence algebraic.
 So all combinations 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha+\beta$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\beta$
\end_inset

, etc..
 are still algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, so they are all in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{F}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Seperable Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn5}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=a_{n}(x-\alpha_{1})^{n_{1}}\cdots(x-\alpha_{k})^{n_{k}}$
\end_inset

 be the factorization of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 in a splitting field, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 are distinct roots and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}\ge1$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
simple root 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn6}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
separable 
\series default
if it has only simple roots.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example5}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=x^{2}+1$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{2}[x]$
\end_inset

 is not separable since 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+1=(x+1)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
\end_document
